<Layout title="🍞 Hoare/Divergence.lean — NonExpanding as threshold triples">
  <main>
    <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/lean/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to lean navigator</a>

    <h1>Hoare/Divergence.lean</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6"><a href="https://github.com/kimjune01/natural-framework/blob/master/NaturalFramework/Hoare/Divergence.lean">View source on GitHub</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Shows that NonExpanding (information measure does not increase) is equivalent to preserving every information-threshold contract &mdash; bridging the metric view to the program logic view.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>theorem nonExpanding_iff_threshold_triple</h3>
    <p>A kernel is non-expanding if and only if it preserves every threshold triple: for all n, <code>&#123;measure &le; n&#125; f &#123;measure &le; n&#125;</code>. A kernel that does not increase information preserves every upper bound on information &mdash; and conversely.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">theorem</span> <span class="text-green-300">nonExpanding_iff_threshold_triple</span> [Monad M] [Support M]
    &#123;f : Kernel M &alpha; &beta;&#125; &#123;m&alpha; : InfoMeasure &alpha;&#125; &#123;m&beta; : InfoMeasure &beta;&#125; :
    NonExpanding f m&alpha; m&beta; &harr;
      &forall; n : Nat, Triple
        (<span class="text-blue-300">fun</span> a =&gt; m&alpha;.measure a &le; n)
        f
        (<span class="text-blue-300">fun</span> b =&gt; m&beta;.measure b &le; n)</code></pre>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Forward direction: if the kernel is non-expanding, then for any input with measure &le; n, every output has measure &le; measure(input) &le; n. Backward direction: pick n = measure(a), and the threshold triple gives measure(b) &le; measure(a).</p>

    <p>This connects to Sato-Katsumata (2023): divergences on a monad give a metric on morphism spaces. NonExpanding is the zero-divergence case. Stating it as a family of Hoare triples connects the metric view to the program logic view. The file notes this is an analogy in spirit, not a formal instance of their relational framework.</p>

    <h3>Connections</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/lean/hoare-core/">Hoare/Core.lean</a> &mdash; imported; the threshold triples are standard Hoare triples</li>
      <li><a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/lean/handshake/">Handshake.lean</a> &mdash; NonExpanding is defined there; this file gives the triple characterization</li>
      <li><a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/lean/hoare-graded/">Hoare/Graded.lean</a> &mdash; graded triples are a richer quantitative view (cost bound per kernel, not just thresholds)</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-8">See also: <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/sato-2023/">🍞 Sato 2023</a> · <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/panangaden-2009/">🍞 Panangaden 2009</a></p>
